See this after reading the uart_docs.


Setting up PuTTY is the final bridge between your Artix-7 hardware and your computer screen. Since your UART is configured for 115200 baud, follow these steps to get the communication line open.

1. Download and Install
Go to the https://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/putty/latest.html 
Download the 64-bit Windows Installer (usually an .msi file).
Run the installer and follow the prompts. Once finished, search for "PuTTY" in your Start menu to open it.

2. Identify your FPGA's COM Port
Before opening PuTTY, you need to know which "door" (COM port) your Nexys A7 is plugged into.
Plug in your FPGA via the micro-USB cable used for programming.
Right-click the Start button and select Device Manager.
Expand the section labeled Ports (COM & LPT).
Look for an entry like USB Serial Port (COMx) or Silicon Labs CP210x USB to UART Bridge (COMx).
Note the number (e.g., COM3 or COM4).

3. Configure PuTTY for your RISC-V SoC
Now, tell PuTTY how to listen to the 1s and 0s coming from your processor.
Connection Type: Select the radio button for Serial.
Serial line: Delete COM1 and type the exact port you found in Device Manager (e.g., COM4).
Speed: Type 115200. This must match the baud rate in your uart.v exactly, or you will see "garbage" characters.
(Optional) Under Category (left side), go to Terminal and check "Implicit LF on every CR" if your text looks like it's stair-stepping across the screen.
Go back to Session at the top. Type a name like "Nexys_A7_UART" in the "Saved Sessions" box and click Save so you don't have to type this every time.

4. Open the Connection
Click Open. A black terminal window will appear.
If your FPGA is currently running the Echo script:
Type a letter on your keyboard.
The character travels to the FPGA, your RISC-V core processes it, and sends it back.
If you see the letter appear in the window, your SoC is officially talking to the world!

Troubleshooting Tips
Blank Screen? If you type and see nothing, ensure your FPGA is programmed with the bitstream and the reset button has been toggled.
Garbage Characters? (e.g., @) This usually means your clock or baud rate math is slightly off. Double-check that your uart.v is truly dividing the 100MHz clock down to 115200.
Once you have this terminal open, are you ready to try sending your first "Hello World" string from the RISC-V assembly code?

To inject your assembly program into the processor, you place it directly into the imem.hex file located in your workspace!

Your RISC-V processor (instr_mem.v) has standard hardware logic that loads this file at boot-up:

verilog
initial begin
    $readmemh("imem.hex", imem);
end
The FPGA and Simulator expects imem.hex to contain bare-metal machine code (one 32-bit hex instruction per line without the 0x). If you have a GCC toolchain on your computer, you would normally compile your code and extract it using riscv64-unknown-elf-objcopy -O verilog.

The Exact Machine Code for the Echo Server
If you just want to get your UART up and running right now without messing with the compiler toolchain, I've manually assembled the exact "WaitRX -> WaitTX -> Echo" assembly program into raw machine code for you!

Just open your imem.hex file, delete what's inside, and paste these exact 10 lines:

text
800000b7
0080a103
00217113
fe010ce3
0040a183
0080a103
00117113
fe011ce3
0030a023
fe1ff06f
What these lines literally mean:
800000b7: lui x1, 0x80000 (Setup UART base 0x8000_0000)
0080a103: WaitRX: lw x2, 8(x1) (Load Status Register)
00217113: andi x2, x2, 2 (Mask rx_ready bit)
fe010ce3: beqz x2, WaitRX (Loop if 0)
0040a183: lw x3, 4(x1) (Load RX character)
0080a103: WaitTX: lw x2, 8(x1) (Load Status Register)
00117113: andi x2, x2, 1 (Mask tx_busy bit)
fe011ce3: bnez x2, WaitTX (Loop if 1)
0030a023: sw x3, 0(x1) (Write/Echo character back out!)
fe1ff06f: j WaitRX (Jump back up to instruction #2)
Once you pasted this into imem.hex, re-run the synthesis on your Nexys A7 FPGA (since the .hex configuration acts as the FPGA's built-in starting ROM) and the program will spring to life! Let me know if PuTTY connects!
